The European Union ha honoured it commitment and responded to this political turnaround at the meeting of the General Affairs Council on 9 October, at which it decided to lift the sanctions, including the oil and air embargoes, imposed on the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia in 1998, with the exception of course of sanction directly aimed at Mr Milosevic and his entourage.
President Kostunica therefore accepted the invitation from the Presidency to go to Biarritz and have lunch with Heads of State and Government.
At the joint press conference he held alongside the French Presidency, Mr Kostunica expressed his heartfelt joy at being welcomed into the European family, for this is exactly what is happening.
The Federal Republic of Yugoslavia will, of course, very soon benefit from the instrument that have been set in place by the Union to cover the entire Balkan region, beginning with the CARDS programme and also the activity of the European Agency for Reconstruction.
Furthermore, the General Affairs Council confirmed the Union' s intention to contribute to re-establishing navigation on the Danube and to actively participate in modernising infrastructure in the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia within a regional context.
Moreover, without prejudice to a need assessment and the coordination of economic and financial assistance to the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, which are to be the joint responsibility of the European Commission and the World Bank, the Biarritz European Council decided to grant the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia initial emergency humanitarian aid totalling EUR 200 million.
Lastly, and I will end here - this is without doubt the most important decision in the medium and long term - the Union ha decided to provide this country with a political prospect by proposing that it conclude a stabilisation and association agreement along the line of those currently being negotiated with the other country in the same region.
It wa precisely with this in mind that President Kostunica wa invited, a you will be aware, to take part in the summit meeting between the European Union and the country of the western Balkans, which is to be held in Zagreb, at the instigation of the President of the French Republic, on 24 November.
These are the issue that can be singled out concerning the development and situation in Serbia and their repercussion for the Union.
I feel that the important thing wa for the Union to very swiftly communicate to this country not only a tangible message of encouragement but also, and I would stress this point, the political prospect of it full and comprehensive integration into the European family.
I believe that this message ha been clearly given.
We can only hope that the process of democratisation is able to continue under optimum conditions.
These, in a nutshell, were the result of the Biarritz European Council which was, and I say this in all sincerity because I believe it to be true, highly productive and therefore of great value to the step forward that the Union is of course still to complete.
Madam President, I would now, in turn, like to give the Commission' s impression following the Biarritz European Council, to which you, Madam President, made an active contribution, along with another eminent member of this House, Mrs Méndez de Vigo, who presented the result of work on the Charter of Fundamental Rights.
The President-in-Office of the Council, Mr Moscovici, ha spoken of something that he ha dubbed the 'Biarritz spirit' .
One might talk of the Biarritz spirit or frame of mind, and also the climate at Biarritz.
Ladies and gentlemen, I can truly say that the climate in which discussion took place genuinely matched the climatic condition that prevailed in Biarritz for the two day we were there.
The weather wa cloudy and windy but it was, all thing considered, an invigorating climate and, I felt, just the type of dynamic climate that we needed at that stage of the discussions, in which I myself noticed many stumbling blocks, far more stumbling block than can always be explained away by the delicacy of the issues.
We needed this invigorating climate, a Mr Moscovici ha said, and I too sensed among the Heads of State and of Government a very solemn air of collective and historic responsibility at this historic juncture for European integration.
There seemed to be a genuine sense of purpose and, in any event, the will to achieve real reform at Nice.
Much ha been said, in the press and elsewhere, of the rift between larger States and smaller States, or le populous countries.
These divergence of opinion are a fact.
Everyone is conscious of them, but there is none of the hostility which is sometimes described.
In this connection, I would prefer to talk of a moment of truth in the debate, rather than a moment of crisis.
Above all, I would like to say, a someone who has, from the start and on a daily basis, been involved in these discussion a one of the workmen, alongside your representative Mr Brok and Professor Tsatsos, that this rift is not the only one that might exist between large and small States.
It is not even, it would seem to me, the central issue in these discussion if one recalls, and this is something that must be remembered and recalled, that ever since the process of European integration began, there ha never been a case, either in the Council or within the Commission, of large country forming a coalition against small countries, or of small States forming a coalition against large countries.
This run counter to the spirit of the Community.
As regard my feeling on this matter, I am aware of and understand the sensitivity of the issue that the Minister ha described, issue which directly relate to the position, the role, and the influence of each country.
I perceived this sensitivity during the visit I made to each of the Member States, and also last week in Athens, with regard both to the Commission, with each country concerned at the position that would be assigned to it, and to the voting system, with each country concerned at the number of vote it is to have in the Council.
Ladies and gentlemen, we must find a solution to these two issues, which will in fact only be resolved when negotiation are complete, and on which we must reach total agreement if that agreement is to mean anything at all.
With regard to the Commission, a solution must be found that preserve it effectiveness, it credibility, and if possible it collegiate nature.
With regard to the voting system, we must find a solution which respect - a both the Commission and the European Parliament have proposed - the twofold legitimacy of, on the one hand, the Member States and, on the other, the people of Europe.
But if I had to tell you spontaneously and very sincerely how I felt, I would say this: regardless of the sensitivity of these issue - the composition of the Commission and the voting system - they cannot be used a criterion for assessing whether Nice is a success or a failure.
The success or failure of the Nice Council will depend on the ability of the Heads of State and Government, and on the ability of Parliament and the Commission, a party to the negotiations, to preserve or consolidate the Community model.
In saying this, lady and gentlemen, I have in mind a number of point that are still under discussion.
Whether the Community system is preserved or weakened will depend on the scope of qualified majority voting and thus of codecision being extended to cover real issues.
That is my first point.
The preservation or strengthening of the Community model will be assessed on the basis of whether we have been able to resist the temptation felt by some to call into question the exclusivity of the Commission' s power to initiate legislation.
I am referring here to Article 250, for which some would like to introduce qualified majority voting.
The preservation and consolidation of the Community system will be assessed on the basis of whether the Commission ha been reserved a fitting role in closer cooperation, and not only a concern the first pillar.
The consolidation of the Community system will be assessed on the basis of whether the role of agency ha been allowed to develop to the detriment of the regulatory authority that belongs to the Commission.
That, lady and gentlemen, from my viewpoint a someone who, let me repeat in all modesty, is one of the humble workman in these discussions, is what I say and think is the way to gauge whether or not genuine reform ha been achieved in Nice.
I would like to follow what the Minister ha said by quickly touching on some of the point that I have just mentioned.
Qualified majority voting: I would stress that the issue is not really about how many field could be changed from unanimity to qualified majority voting.
The real issue is the status of these fields, and the great merit of the Biarritz Summit will have been that of defining the most problematic area and encouraging us, or authorising us, to find technical solution for taxation issues, or in any case for the small section of taxation policy, or of social protection, which relates directly to the internal market.
There is a need to reassure those who are worried that under no circumstance will the sovereignty of the Member States in taxation matter be challenged, and to also tell those who have worry that the idea is not to merge social protection systems, especially from the bottom up, but simply to see to it that the common market and the single market run smoothly within an enlarged Europe.
Trade policy, asylum and immigration, cohesion policy, environmental policy: in each of these field several approach to solution have been sounded out and, a early a yesterday morning, the group of representative wa back at work.
Following on from what Mr Moscovici ha said, I would like to state that the Commission is no mere bystander in this work.
It is playing it part and is ready and willing, alongside the Presidency, to seek out the fairest solutions.
Ladies and gentlemen, we must quite simply see to it that from now on we keep alive the spirit and climate of Biarritz a regard these qualified majority voting issues.
Naturally, a regard all these areas, where the transition to qualified majority voting is involved, I would like to reiterate our intention to extend codecision where legislative matter are concerned.
As Mr Moscovici ha said, genuine progress ha also been made concerning closer cooperation.
It is interesting to note that many delegation feel that we have to turn this progress on closer cooperation to good account, and this is along the line of what I wa saying earlier, in order to strengthen the role of the Community institution - the role of the Commission, but also that of Parliament.
I feel that the fundamental demand made by Parliament and the Commission will be met or honoured, and that on this point we will manage to secure the abolition of recourse to the European Council, which is to say the right of veto, along with a lowering of the quorum to one third, or eight, of the Member States in Community matters.
It wa made eminently clear at Biarritz that closer cooperation would constitute an additional force for integration and not an instrument of exclusion.
I also feel that an agreement could be reached on another theme, on Article 7, taking a a basis or a pointer the proposal that the Commission itself made to provide for vigorous Community dialogue on legal matters, and Community and political control of crisis situation in which we might find ourselves due to the stance that one government or another adopts with regard to our common values.
Mr Moscovici ha spoken of the Charter.
In drafting this instrument, work of high quality ha been carried out in an original and intelligent manner.
I feel that it will go on to be proclaimed at Nice, and this already mark a great step forward.
We cannot stop there and at Nice we will need to envisage way of addressing the place that this Charter is to have within the Treaties.
Let u not wait until after Nice to consider the post-Nice scenario regarding a number of issue of a constitutional nature: that of the role of the Charter, and thus of the formal consolidation of citizens' rights, that of the simplification of the Treaties, on which we have worked with the Institute of Florence, that of the clarification or focussing of competences, so that we can finally say who is doing what within the European Union, what the Union is or is not doing, or what it should stop doing.
These are issue that we do not have time to deal with thoroughly prior to Nice, but they must be raised and would perhaps merit in-depth attention after Nice.
Ladies and gentlemen, there are still a great many thorny issue in these complex negotiation which can only be resolved by universal agreement. I would like to confirm that the Biarritz spirit or the Biarritz climate would seem to me to have been primarily one of determination.
We are still some way off an agreement, but I would like, a regard the determined support the Commission offer you, to give a clear reminder, if there could be any doubts, concern or question surrounding this, that the Commission will strive to the very last minute - you can count on me - to set itself very ambitious target for the Treaty of Nice in these negotiations, so that we will not simply be concluding the negotiation at Nice, but first and foremost ensuring their success.
Madam President, I will quickly mention some other issues, if I may, to confirm or expand upon what the Presidency ha said.
First, Serbia.
Everyone here ha been deeply moved and heartened by the move to democracy in Serbia - firstly by the will of the people of Serbia and by the election of President Kostunica a President of the Yugoslav Federation.
This is what ha caused the European Union to radically alter it policy in respect of Serbia.
I must say that President Kostunica' s visit to Biarritz wa an important and moving event which marked the return of Serbia to the European fold.
In more practical terms, we announced that emergency aid totalling EUR 200 million had been allocated to Serbia, and the Commission is soon to present a package of emergency measure that will cater for the country' s priority need a winter approaches.
Besides the emergency aid, there can be no doubt that Serbia will also need, a Mr Moscovici ha indicated, more comprehensive support, which will be implemented in association with the World Bank and the EIB among others.
