I am particularly addressing the group that are blocking this decision in Parliament, starting with the Group of the European People' s Party (Christian Democrats) and European Democrats.
Then there is the matter of the Charter of Fundamental Rights.
If we all agree that the Charter is a very important document, which we all support and which, furthermore, is a symbol of collective identity, I cannot understand what we are going to do with the Charter.
Are we going to keep it in a box?
Are we going to save it for a rainy day?
In my opinion, it should be the frontispiece of a future Constitution, but at the moment, what we could do and what could easily be achieved in Nice, is to include the Charter in the Treaty by mean of an extremely simple link: Article 6(2) of the Treaty on European Union.
I would ask the Commission and the Council to make a statement on this matter.
This is an important topic for current and future Member States.
In this respect I would also like to address my colleague in the European People' s Party - and I would ask Mr Poettering to listen to me - because what we advocate in this Assembly, we should also advocate outside it.
It is also absolutely unacceptable that Mr Berlusconi' s party in the Italian Parliament voted against this Charter and that a Member of this Assembly used coarse, pre or post-fascist language in relation to the Charter.
We must be coherent and uphold the Charter here and in our own national parliaments.
We must do so because these value are essential for everyone.
In this respect, I would also ask that a clear announcement be made regarding the proposal we are making, a we believe it make political sense.
In conclusion, Madam President, two final comment regarding fundamental matter of external policy.
On the one hand, the presence of President Kostunica wa an historic event.
The important thing is that we help the Balkans to achieve stability, not instability.
To this end, I believe that we should apply the same standard to all.
We cannot ask Croatia to cooperate with the International Court and not demand the same of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.
We must find money - and here the Council ha responsibility - to assert our community of value and create a balanced, stabilising policy in the Balkans.
With regard to the Middle East, it is clear that one of the cause of the situation - not the only cause, a this matter is far more complex - is that the European Union in the past wa vetoed a a potential mediator.
The step that ha been taken should be applauded, although it wa in a situation in which responsibility had to be shared.
I believe that we must honour our commitment in one of the most tragic situation we are experiencing today.
Madam President, firstly I praise the European Council for accepting the draft Charter a definitive.
From what we know of the performance of the Prime Ministers and Presidents at Biarritz on the trickiest question of Treaty reform, the Charter will probably become the greatest trophy at Nice.
So why is the French Presidency trying to suppress the question of the installation of the Charter within the Treaty?
President Chirac, with his usual capacity for surprise, said in his press statement that the Charter' s legal status would be a question for the Swedish Presidency.
What doe that mean?
What on earth is Sweden supposed to achieve that France cannot?
